{"parentUuid":"303244b0-f89c-4d85-95f6-e1af039b2cd5","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01WP92ZaZvmLh7fFpjezceMy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Wf6TszzzEi7rEBJACCSbvV","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning","prompt":"Extract the concrete mechanism: how is a skill learned/extracted from a trajectory? How are skills stored, retrieved, injected into context? How does a verifier or pass/fail signal refine/prune skills? What are the exact performance numbers (e.g. +9%, +15.7%, benchmark names like Terminal-Bench), and what specifically drove the improvement? Quote numbers and benchmark names exactly."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1449,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2179,"cache_read_input_tokens":12353,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2179,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqLGR5YV74PkQL1sBuU","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"96a5f505-23b8-43a6-a38b-4c12f1dd9093","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:15.204Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"96a5f505-23b8-43a6-a38b-4c12f1dd9093","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01WP92ZaZvmLh7fFpjezceMy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01V3RTnsUBxphA4diWVKMAR7","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"ExpeL experiential learning LLM agent insights transfer arxiv"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1449,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2179,"cache_read_input_tokens":12353,"output_tokens":335,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2179},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1449,"output_tokens":335,"cache_read_input_tokens":12353,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2179,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2179,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqLGR5YV74PkQL1sBuU","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"feaa739e-a5c8-40c3-b7f7-d9eb53ac6bd5","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:15.472Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"96a5f505-23b8-43a6-a38b-4c12f1dd9093","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Wf6TszzzEi7rEBJACCSbvV","type":"tool_result","content":"# Skill Learning: Mechanism & Performance\n\n## Learning Mechanism\n\nThe paper describes a **two-stage process**:\n\n1. **Reflection Stage**: Given a task trajectory, the system generates evaluation assessing task success, reasoning soundness, edge case handling, and \"repetitive patterns or actions that could be abstracted.\"\n\n2. **Creation Stage**: A learning agent powered by Letta Code uses Anthropic's skill-creator to \"generate a skill that provides potential approaches, common pitfalls, and verification strategies.\"\n\nCrucially, the reflection stage can be enhanced with textual feedback from task verifiers identifying failure modes.\n\n## Storage & Injection\n\nSkills are stored as **markdown files** designed to be \"modular and can be managed by git.\" The retrieval/injection mechanism isn't explicitly detailed, but the paper indicates agents dynamically access skills during task execution within the Letta Code harness.\n\n## Performance Metrics (Exact)\n\nTested on **Terminal Bench 2.0** (89 tasks):\n\n- **Trajectory-only skills**: \"21.1% relative (9% absolute) increase\" with \"15.7% reduction in costs and 10.4% reduction in tool calls\"\n- **Trajectory + feedback skills**: \"additional 6.7% improvement, leading to an overall gain of 36.8% relative (15.7% absolute) over the baseline\"\n\nThe improvement driver was explicit: feedback-informed skills better encode \"common failure modes and unsuccessful approaches\" versus trajectory-alone learning.\n\n## Verifier Role\n\nThe verifier provides \"textual feedback\" from test logs, but no explicit pruning mechanism is described—only that richer feedback context improves skill quality."}]},"uuid":"494a27e0-ed37-48f0-819c-0fb67bb492a4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:21.074Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":30727,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Skill Learning: Mechanism & Performance\n\n## Learning Mechanism\n\nThe paper describes a **two-stage process**:\n\n1. **Reflection Stage**: Given a task trajectory, the system generates evaluation assessing task success, reasoning soundness, edge case handling, and \"repetitive patterns or actions that could be abstracted.\"\n\n2. **Creation Stage**: A learning agent powered by Letta Code uses Anthropic's skill-creator to \"generate a skill that provides potential approaches, common pitfalls, and verification strategies.\"\n\nCrucially, the reflection stage can be enhanced with textual feedback from task verifiers identifying failure modes.\n\n## Storage & Injection\n\nSkills are stored as **markdown files** designed to be \"modular and can be managed by git.\" The retrieval/injection mechanism isn't explicitly detailed, but the paper indicates agents dynamically access skills during task execution within the Letta Code harness.\n\n## Performance Metrics (Exact)\n\nTested on **Terminal Bench 2.0** (89 tasks):\n\n- **Trajectory-only skills**: \"21.1% relative (9% absolute) increase\" with \"15.7% reduction in costs and 10.4% reduction in tool calls\"\n- **Trajectory + feedback skills**: \"additional 6.7% improvement, leading to an overall gain of 36.8% relative (15.7% absolute) over the baseline\"\n\nThe improvement driver was explicit: feedback-informed skills better encode \"common failure modes and unsuccessful approaches\" versus trajectory-alone learning.\n\n## Verifier Role\n\nThe verifier provides \"textual feedback\" from test logs, but no explicit pruning mechanism is described—only that richer feedback context improves skill quality.","durationMs":5692,"url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"96a5f505-23b8-43a6-a38b-4c12f1dd9093","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"feaa739e-a5c8-40c3-b7f7-d9eb53ac6bd5","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01V3RTnsUBxphA4diWVKMAR7","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"ExpeL experiential learning LLM agent insights transfer arxiv\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[2308.10144v1] ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144v1\"},{\"title\":\"[2308.10144] ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144\"},{\"title\":\"[2308.10144v2] ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144v2\"},{\"title\":\"[2308.10144v3] ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144v3\"},{\"title\":\"ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2308.10144\"},{\"title\":\"ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2308.10144v2\"},{\"title\":\"Experiential Reflective Learning for Self-Improving LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.24639\"},{\"title\":\"[2603.24639] Experiential Reflective Learning for Self-Improving LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.24639\"},{\"title\":\"[2603.24639v2] Experiential Reflective Learning for Self-Improving LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.24639v2\"}]\n\nI found relevant search results about ExpeL and experiential learning in LLM agents. Here's what the search revealed:\n\n## ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners\n\nThe Experiential Learning (ExpeL) agent autonomously gathers experiences and extracts knowledge using natural language from a collection of training tasks. At inference, the agent recalls its extracted insights and past experiences to make informed decisions.\n\n### Motivation\n\nWhile there is a growing demand to tailor LLMs for custom decision-making tasks, finetuning them for specific tasks is resource-intensive and may diminish the model's generalization capabilities. Moreover, state-of-the-art language models like GPT-4 and Claude are primarily accessible through API calls, with their parametric weights remaining proprietary and unavailable to the public.\n\n### Key Results\n\nThe empirical results highlight the robust learning efficacy of the ExpeL agent, indicating a consistent enhancement in its performance as it accumulates experiences. The research further explores the emerging capabilities and transfer learning potential of the ExpeL agent through qualitative observations and additional experiments.\n\n### Transfer Learning\n\nThe research investigates a setting where knowledge accumulated from a source task distribution could be useful for a target task distribution with minimal target task examples. Like most transfer learning settings, they assume that the source and target tasks exhibit common knowledge, and experiences accumulated from source tasks can benefit the agent in solving a new set of target tasks.\n\nThe paper was published on arXiv as document 2308.10144.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"a8313b24-a414-40ac-bae5-5034b43dcf3c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:23.911Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"ExpeL experiential learning LLM agent insights transfer arxiv","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01WzpDExSMr9goDWFd1K6KAg","content":[{"title":"[2308.10144v1] ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144v1"},{"title":"[2308.10144] ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144"},{"title":"[2308.10144v2] ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144v2"},{"title":"[2308.10144v3] ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144v3"},{"title":"ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2308.10144"},{"title":"ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2308.10144v2"},{"title":"Experiential Reflective Learning for Self-Improving LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.24639"},{"title":"[2603.24639] Experiential Reflective Learning for Self-Improving LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.24639"},{"title":"[2603.24639v2] Experiential Reflective Learning for Self-Improving LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.24639v2"}]},"I found relevant search results about ExpeL and experiential learning in LLM agents. Here's what the search revealed:\n\n## ExpeL: LLM Agents Are Experiential Learners\n\nThe Experiential Learning (ExpeL) agent autonomously gathers experiences and extracts knowledge using natural language from a collection of training tasks. At inference, the agent recalls its extracted insights and past experiences to make informed decisions.\n\n### Motivation\n\nWhile there is a growing demand to tailor LLMs for custom decision-making tasks, finetuning them for specific tasks is resource-intensive and may diminish the model's generalization capabilities. Moreover, state-of-the-art language models like GPT-4 and Claude are primarily accessible through API calls, with their parametric weights remaining proprietary and unavailable to the public.\n\n### Key Results\n\nThe empirical results highlight the robust learning efficacy of the ExpeL agent, indicating a consistent enhancement in its performance as it accumulates experiences. The research further explores the emerging capabilities and transfer learning potential of the ExpeL agent through qualitative observations and additional experiments.\n\n### Transfer Learning\n\nThe research investigates a setting where knowledge accumulated from a source task distribution could be useful for a target task distribution with minimal target task examples. Like most transfer learning settings, they assume that the source and target tasks exhibit common knowledge, and experiences accumulated from source tasks can benefit the agent in solving a new set of target tasks.\n\nThe paper was published on arXiv as document 2308.10144."],"durationSeconds":8.06032166699972,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"feaa739e-a5c8-40c3-b7f7-d9eb53ac6bd5","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
