{"parentUuid":"1d3c86e5-3c13-41e1-97e5-286250f89626","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01B2Fh6SbbmHmU89Vchnkeex","type":"tool_result","content":"# ExpeL: Mechanism Overview\n\nBased on the provided arXiv page, I can only offer limited details about ExpeL's concrete mechanisms, as the abstract doesn't contain specific technical implementation information.\n\n## What the Abstract Reveals\n\nThe abstract states that ExpeL agents:\n\n- \"autonomously gathers experiences and extracts knowledge using natural language from a collection of training tasks\"\n- \"recalls its extracted insights and past experiences to make informed decisions\"\n- Shows \"consistent enhancement in its performance as it accumulates experiences\"\n\n## Critical Limitation\n\nThe webpage excerpt provided **does not include** detailed information about:\n- Specific insight extraction operations (ADD, EDIT, DOWNVOTE, UPVOTE)\n- Successful vs. failed trajectory comparison mechanisms\n- Storage and retrieval processes (top-k similarity methods)\n- Prompt injection techniques\n- Benchmark results with numerical performance improvements on HotpotQA, ALFWorld, or WebShop\n\n## Next Steps\n\nTo obtain the technical details you're requesting, you would need to access the full paper via the \"[View PDF](/pdf/2308.10144)\" or \"[HTML (experimental)](https://arxiv.org/html/2308.10144v3)\" links provided on the arXiv page. The abstract alone cannot provide the specific quantitative results and algorithmic details you've requested."}]},"uuid":"1a3b43ff-dc3c-4eca-bfbd-efc8a823aafa","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:33.275Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":48018,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# ExpeL: Mechanism Overview\n\nBased on the provided arXiv page, I can only offer limited details about ExpeL's concrete mechanisms, as the abstract doesn't contain specific technical implementation information.\n\n## What the Abstract Reveals\n\nThe abstract states that ExpeL agents:\n\n- \"autonomously gathers experiences and extracts knowledge using natural language from a collection of training tasks\"\n- \"recalls its extracted insights and past experiences to make informed decisions\"\n- Shows \"consistent enhancement in its performance as it accumulates experiences\"\n\n## Critical Limitation\n\nThe webpage excerpt provided **does not include** detailed information about:\n- Specific insight extraction operations (ADD, EDIT, DOWNVOTE, UPVOTE)\n- Successful vs. failed trajectory comparison mechanisms\n- Storage and retrieval processes (top-k similarity methods)\n- Prompt injection techniques\n- Benchmark results with numerical performance improvements on HotpotQA, ALFWorld, or WebShop\n\n## Next Steps\n\nTo obtain the technical details you're requesting, you would need to access the full paper via the \"[View PDF](/pdf/2308.10144)\" or \"[HTML (experimental)](https://arxiv.org/html/2308.10144v3)\" links provided on the arXiv page. The abstract alone cannot provide the specific quantitative results and algorithmic details you've requested.","durationMs":4028,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"1d3c86e5-3c13-41e1-97e5-286250f89626","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"ea25c22b-b575-416e-81fb-74ef2068aabd","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FiVPgY6Gwu9KzuajgLENfW","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Agent Workflow Memory AWM induction reusable routines arxiv WebArena\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Paper page - Agent Workflow Memory\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/papers/2409.07429\"},{\"title\":\"[2409.07429] Agent Workflow Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.07429\"},{\"title\":\"[2409.07429v1] Agent Workflow Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.07429v1\"},{\"title\":\"Agent Workflow Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2409.07429v1\"},{\"title\":\"Agent Workflow Memory\",\"url\":\"https://www.summarizepaper.com/en/arxiv-id/2409.07429v1/\"},{\"title\":\"[Research Paper Summary]Agent Workflow Memory | by Mehnoor Aijaz | Athina AI | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/athina-ai/research-paper-summary-agent-workflow-memory-35318865b65f\"},{\"title\":\"AGENT WORKFLOW MEMORY Zora Zhiruo Wang Jiayuan Mao Daniel Fried Graham Neubig\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2409.07429\"}]\n\nI found relevant information about Agent Workflow Memory (AWM). Here's what the search returned:\n\n## Overview\n\nAgent Workflow Memory (AWM) enhances language model-based agents' performance on complex tasks by inducing and using reusable task workflows, resulting in improved success rates and reduced steps compared to baselines.\n\n## Method\n\nAWM is a method for inducing commonly reused routines (workflows) and selectively providing workflows to the agent to guide subsequent generations, and it flexibly applies to both offline and online scenarios, where agents induce workflows from training examples beforehand or from test queries on the fly.\n\n## Experimental Results\n\nThe research was conducted on two major web navigation benchmarks -- Mind2Web and WebArena -- that collectively cover 1000+ tasks from 200+ domains across travel, shopping, and social media, and AWM substantially improves the baseline results by 24.6% and 51.1% relative success rate on Mind2Web and WebArena while reducing the number of steps taken to solve WebArena tasks successfully.\n\n## Generalization\n\nOnline AWM robustly generalizes in cross-task, website, and domain evaluations, surpassing baselines from 8.9 to 14.0 absolute points as train-test task distribution gaps widen.\n\nThe paper (arxiv:2409.07429) was published in September 2024.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"bd33c4de-880d-498a-b49b-542e9b885fff","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:37.500Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Agent Workflow Memory AWM induction reusable routines arxiv WebArena","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Ciy9oq9p3dkDTD8xFum5NN","content":[{"title":"Paper page - Agent Workflow Memory","url":"https://huggingface.co/papers/2409.07429"},{"title":"[2409.07429] Agent Workflow Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.07429"},{"title":"[2409.07429v1] Agent Workflow Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.07429v1"},{"title":"Agent Workflow Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2409.07429v1"},{"title":"Agent Workflow Memory","url":"https://www.summarizepaper.com/en/arxiv-id/2409.07429v1/"},{"title":"[Research Paper Summary]Agent Workflow Memory | by Mehnoor Aijaz | Athina AI | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/athina-ai/research-paper-summary-agent-workflow-memory-35318865b65f"},{"title":"AGENT WORKFLOW MEMORY Zora Zhiruo Wang Jiayuan Mao Daniel Fried Graham Neubig","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2409.07429"}]},"I found relevant information about Agent Workflow Memory (AWM). Here's what the search returned:\n\n## Overview\n\nAgent Workflow Memory (AWM) enhances language model-based agents' performance on complex tasks by inducing and using reusable task workflows, resulting in improved success rates and reduced steps compared to baselines.\n\n## Method\n\nAWM is a method for inducing commonly reused routines (workflows) and selectively providing workflows to the agent to guide subsequent generations, and it flexibly applies to both offline and online scenarios, where agents induce workflows from training examples beforehand or from test queries on the fly.\n\n## Experimental Results\n\nThe research was conducted on two major web navigation benchmarks -- Mind2Web and WebArena -- that collectively cover 1000+ tasks from 200+ domains across travel, shopping, and social media, and AWM substantially improves the baseline results by 24.6% and 51.1% relative success rate on Mind2Web and WebArena while reducing the number of steps taken to solve WebArena tasks successfully.\n\n## Generalization\n\nOnline AWM robustly generalizes in cross-task, website, and domain evaluations, surpassing baselines from 8.9 to 14.0 absolute points as train-test task distribution gaps widen.\n\nThe paper (arxiv:2409.07429) was published in September 2024."],"durationSeconds":7.811964000000619,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ea25c22b-b575-416e-81fb-74ef2068aabd","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"ebfa7f90-6323-49d9-9ea9-be53a85b987a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Py4tSgsRjGRfHwQJJVGa7L","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Reflexion verbal reinforcement learning episodic memory arxiv self-reflection\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Reflexion: language agents with verbal reinforcement learning | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=vAElhFcKW6\"},{\"title\":\"[2303.11366] Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning\",\"url\":\"https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2303.11366\"},{\"title\":\"Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2303.11366\"},{\"title\":\"[2303.11366] Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366\"},{\"title\":\"Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning Noah Shinn\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2303.11366\"},{\"title\":\"[2303.11366v4] Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366v4\"},{\"title\":\"Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning Noah Shinn\",\"url\":\"https://proceedings.neurips.cc/paper_files/paper/2023/file/1b44b878bb782e6954cd888628510e90-Paper-Conference.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Reflexion: language agents with verbal reinforcement ...\",\"url\":\"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.5555/3666122.3666499\"},{\"title\":\"Position Paper: Towards Open Complex Human-AI Agents Collaboration Systems for Problem Solving and Knowledge Management\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.00018\"}]\n\nI found comprehensive information about Reflexion. Here are the key details from the search results:\n\n## Overview\n\nReflexion is a novel framework to reinforce language agents not by updating weights, but instead through linguistic feedback.\n\n## Core Mechanism\n\nReflexion agents verbally reflect on task feedback signals, then maintain their own reflective text in an episodic memory buffer to induce better decision-making in subsequent trials. Reflexion converts binary or scalar feedback from the environment into verbal feedback in the form of a textual summary, which is then added as additional context for the LLM agent in the next episode. This self-reflective feedback acts as a 'semantic' gradient signal by providing the agent with a concrete direction to improve upon, helping it learn from prior mistakes to perform better on the task.\n\n## Problem It Addresses\n\nLarge language models (LLMs) have been increasingly used to interact with external environments (e.g., games, compilers, APIs) as goal-driven agents. However, it remains challenging for these language agents to quickly and efficiently learn from trial-and-error as traditional reinforcement learning methods require extensive training samples and expensive model fine-tuning.\n\n## Research Findings\n\nSelf-reflection is extremely useful to learn complex tasks over a handful of trials. Additionally, self-reflection improves learning by an 8% absolute boost over the episodic memory learning advantage. This result supports the argument that refinement-only approaches are not as effective as self-reflection-guided refinement approaches.\n\nThe paper was published as part of NeurIPS 2023 proceedings and is available on arXiv as paper 2303.11366.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"481e01ee-a3c8-4d57-9dec-4771e03e12ae","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:37.741Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Reflexion verbal reinforcement learning episodic memory arxiv self-reflection","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_015ndxqp2GdADBBWtVAMLC2A","content":[{"title":"Reflexion: language agents with verbal reinforcement learning | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=vAElhFcKW6"},{"title":"[2303.11366] Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning","url":"https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2303.11366"},{"title":"Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2303.11366"},{"title":"[2303.11366] Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366"},{"title":"Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning Noah Shinn","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2303.11366"},{"title":"[2303.11366v4] Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366v4"},{"title":"Reflexion: Language Agents with Verbal Reinforcement Learning Noah Shinn","url":"https://proceedings.neurips.cc/paper_files/paper/2023/file/1b44b878bb782e6954cd888628510e90-Paper-Conference.pdf"},{"title":"Reflexion: language agents with verbal reinforcement ...","url":"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.5555/3666122.3666499"},{"title":"Position Paper: Towards Open Complex Human-AI Agents Collaboration Systems for Problem Solving and Knowledge Management","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.00018"}]},"I found comprehensive information about Reflexion. Here are the key details from the search results:\n\n## Overview\n\nReflexion is a novel framework to reinforce language agents not by updating weights, but instead through linguistic feedback.\n\n## Core Mechanism\n\nReflexion agents verbally reflect on task feedback signals, then maintain their own reflective text in an episodic memory buffer to induce better decision-making in subsequent trials. Reflexion converts binary or scalar feedback from the environment into verbal feedback in the form of a textual summary, which is then added as additional context for the LLM agent in the next episode. This self-reflective feedback acts as a 'semantic' gradient signal by providing the agent with a concrete direction to improve upon, helping it learn from prior mistakes to perform better on the task.\n\n## Problem It Addresses\n\nLarge language models (LLMs) have been increasingly used to interact with external environments (e.g., games, compilers, APIs) as goal-driven agents. However, it remains challenging for these language agents to quickly and efficiently learn from trial-and-error as traditional reinforcement learning methods require extensive training samples and expensive model fine-tuning.\n\n## Research Findings\n\nSelf-reflection is extremely useful to learn complex tasks over a handful of trials. Additionally, self-reflection improves learning by an 8% absolute boost over the episodic memory learning advantage. This result supports the argument that refinement-only approaches are not as effective as self-reflection-guided refinement approaches.\n\nThe paper was published as part of NeurIPS 2023 proceedings and is available on arXiv as paper 2303.11366."],"durationSeconds":7.693218084000051,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ebfa7f90-6323-49d9-9ea9-be53a85b987a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
