{"parentUuid":"f5f68ae2-2324-4526-b2ae-07a44e53feff","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_016L5xqFxTAMgJwikwKCdafz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01GsMuVHYENZbmcJFqcq9hcF","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2308.10144v3","prompt":"Extract ExpeL's concrete mechanism for insight extraction: what operations are used to maintain the insight pool (ADD, UPVOTE, DOWNVOTE, EDIT)? How does it compare successful vs failed trajectory pairs to extract insights? How are past experiences retrieved at inference (top-k by similarity using Faiss/embeddings)? How are insights + retrieved examples injected into the prompt? What benchmarks (HotpotQA, ALFWorld, WebShop, FEVER) and what improvement numbers? Quote exact numbers."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3112,"cache_read_input_tokens":18038,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3112,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqNJMiXnmYVD6H9ygoE","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"efabd095-94c4-4785-bdfe-fbfc1211a9e9","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:44.566Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"efabd095-94c4-4785-bdfe-fbfc1211a9e9","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_016L5xqFxTAMgJwikwKCdafz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01TUzq9WJgiCya68QNDghBXr","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning","prompt":"What does this post say about continual learning in token space, memory blocks, and how it relates to skill learning? Any specific mechanism for turning experience into reusable memory, and any benchmark numbers?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3112,"cache_read_input_tokens":18038,"output_tokens":482,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3112},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":323,"output_tokens":482,"cache_read_input_tokens":18038,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3112,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3112,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqNJMiXnmYVD6H9ygoE","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"7d305828-fc0d-41be-b6e4-9badc8344b7d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:45.815Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"7d305828-fc0d-41be-b6e4-9badc8344b7d","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TUzq9WJgiCya68QNDghBXr","type":"tool_result","content":"# Continual Learning in Token Space: Key Points\n\n## Core Concept\nThe post argues that AI agents should learn primarily through updating **context tokens** rather than model weights. As stated: \"updates to learned context, not weights, should be the primary mechanism for LLM agents to learn from experience.\"\n\n## Memory Management Approach\nRather than simply appending experience until context overflows, the post proposes **\"sleep-time compute\"** for memory refinement—background processing that consolidates, identifies contradictions, and abstracts patterns from experiences between active sessions.\n\nThe post also advocates for \"teaching agents to manage their own memory,\" suggesting agents need explicit training to recognize when context degrades and actively restructure their own learned context.\n\n## Advantages Over Weight-Based Learning\nToken-space learning offers:\n- **Interpretability**: \"Token-space memories are human-readable\"\n- **Portability**: Memories transfer across models and generations\n- **Control**: Easy checkpointing, rollback, and versioning\n\n## Benchmark Numbers\nThe post contains **no specific performance metrics or benchmarks**. It's a conceptual research argument rather than an empirical study with quantified results.\n\n## Skill Learning\nThe post doesn't detail a specific mechanism for converting experience into reusable skills, only suggesting that learned context could eventually be distilled into model weights for efficiency gains."}]},"uuid":"423d9a80-2251-4fe5-bff4-eab3d5c274ed","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:50.353Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":75673,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Continual Learning in Token Space: Key Points\n\n## Core Concept\nThe post argues that AI agents should learn primarily through updating **context tokens** rather than model weights. As stated: \"updates to learned context, not weights, should be the primary mechanism for LLM agents to learn from experience.\"\n\n## Memory Management Approach\nRather than simply appending experience until context overflows, the post proposes **\"sleep-time compute\"** for memory refinement—background processing that consolidates, identifies contradictions, and abstracts patterns from experiences between active sessions.\n\nThe post also advocates for \"teaching agents to manage their own memory,\" suggesting agents need explicit training to recognize when context degrades and actively restructure their own learned context.\n\n## Advantages Over Weight-Based Learning\nToken-space learning offers:\n- **Interpretability**: \"Token-space memories are human-readable\"\n- **Portability**: Memories transfer across models and generations\n- **Control**: Easy checkpointing, rollback, and versioning\n\n## Benchmark Numbers\nThe post contains **no specific performance metrics or benchmarks**. It's a conceptual research argument rather than an empirical study with quantified results.\n\n## Skill Learning\nThe post doesn't detail a specific mechanism for converting experience into reusable skills, only suggesting that learned context could eventually be distilled into model weights for efficiency gains.","durationMs":4315,"url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"7d305828-fc0d-41be-b6e4-9badc8344b7d","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"efabd095-94c4-4785-bdfe-fbfc1211a9e9","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GsMuVHYENZbmcJFqcq9hcF","type":"tool_result","content":"# ExpeL's Insight Extraction and Inference Mechanisms\n\n## Insight Extraction Operations\n\nExpeL maintains insights through four LLM-controlled operations on an insight pool:\n\n- **ADD**: Introduces new insights with initial importance count of 2\n- **EDIT**: Modifies existing insights (increments importance count)\n- **UPVOTE**: Agrees with insights (increments importance count)\n- **DOWNVOTE**: Disagrees with insights (decrements importance count)\n\nInsights are removed when importance reaches zero. As stated: \"A newly added insight will have an initial importance count of two associated with it, and the count will increment if subsequent operators UPVOTE or EDIT are applied to it.\"\n\n## Success vs. Failure Comparison\n\nThe system uses two complementary approaches:\n\n1. **Comparative analysis**: Pairs successful trajectories with failed ones from identical tasks, highlighting differences between correct and incorrect actions\n2. **Pattern extraction**: Analyzes L-sized groups of successes across different tasks to identify common \"good practices\"\n\nThe agent receives \"success/fail pairs or a list of L successes\" to dynamically modify insights.\n\n## Inference-Time Experience Retrieval\n\nAt evaluation, the system retrieves similar experiences using: \"all-mpnet-base-v2 embedder to obtain top-k successful trajectories that have the maximum inner-product task similarity with the evaluation task\" via Faiss vectorstore.\n\n## Prompt Injection\n\nDuring inference, task specifications are augmented with: \"concatenation of the full list of extracted insights\" plus \"top-k trajectories with the highest task similarity\" as in-context examples.\n\n## Benchmark Performance\n\n| Benchmark | Improvement |\n|-----------|------------|\n| **HotpotQA** | 39% (ExpeL) vs 28% (ReAct) |\n| **ALFWorld** | 59% (ExpeL) vs 40% (ReAct) |\n| **WebShop** | 49% (ExpeL) vs 11% (ReAct) |\n| **FEVER** (transfer) | 70% (ExpeL Transfer) vs 63% (ReAct) |"}]},"uuid":"548408c7-2e8c-4546-9474-f7f2f0b81541","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:51.681Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":449376,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# ExpeL's Insight Extraction and Inference Mechanisms\n\n## Insight Extraction Operations\n\nExpeL maintains insights through four LLM-controlled operations on an insight pool:\n\n- **ADD**: Introduces new insights with initial importance count of 2\n- **EDIT**: Modifies existing insights (increments importance count)\n- **UPVOTE**: Agrees with insights (increments importance count)\n- **DOWNVOTE**: Disagrees with insights (decrements importance count)\n\nInsights are removed when importance reaches zero. As stated: \"A newly added insight will have an initial importance count of two associated with it, and the count will increment if subsequent operators UPVOTE or EDIT are applied to it.\"\n\n## Success vs. Failure Comparison\n\nThe system uses two complementary approaches:\n\n1. **Comparative analysis**: Pairs successful trajectories with failed ones from identical tasks, highlighting differences between correct and incorrect actions\n2. **Pattern extraction**: Analyzes L-sized groups of successes across different tasks to identify common \"good practices\"\n\nThe agent receives \"success/fail pairs or a list of L successes\" to dynamically modify insights.\n\n## Inference-Time Experience Retrieval\n\nAt evaluation, the system retrieves similar experiences using: \"all-mpnet-base-v2 embedder to obtain top-k successful trajectories that have the maximum inner-product task similarity with the evaluation task\" via Faiss vectorstore.\n\n## Prompt Injection\n\nDuring inference, task specifications are augmented with: \"concatenation of the full list of extracted insights\" plus \"top-k trajectories with the highest task similarity\" as in-context examples.\n\n## Benchmark Performance\n\n| Benchmark | Improvement |\n|-----------|------------|\n| **HotpotQA** | 39% (ExpeL) vs 28% (ReAct) |\n| **ALFWorld** | 59% (ExpeL) vs 40% (ReAct) |\n| **WebShop** | 49% (ExpeL) vs 11% (ReAct) |\n| **FEVER** (transfer) | 70% (ExpeL Transfer) vs 63% (ReAct) |","durationMs":6896,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2308.10144v3"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"efabd095-94c4-4785-bdfe-fbfc1211a9e9","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"548408c7-2e8c-4546-9474-f7f2f0b81541","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Tob4Gsk5ZDJwqbYULwuZ93","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have strong detail now. Let me fetch the Voyager paper for skill library/retrieval/self-verification specifics and AWM for the induction mechanism, to round out the comparison."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":478,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1556,"cache_read_input_tokens":21150,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1556,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqPKu1gjjz1acVPReq9","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"1d5ed6c1-02f0-42b4-8a04-adf2f9316af4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:54.851Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"1d5ed6c1-02f0-42b4-8a04-adf2f9316af4","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Tob4Gsk5ZDJwqbYULwuZ93","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01K9kH91j7K1j8aBdEnxrQjB","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2305.16291","prompt":"Extract Voyager's concrete skill-library mechanism: how is a skill added to the library (only after self-verification passes)? How are skills indexed (embedding of GPT-generated description) and retrieved (top-5 by embedding similarity of the query context)? How does the self-verification module (GPT-4 as critic / success check) gate skill creation? How are retrieved skills injected for new tasks? Quote the 15.3x faster tech tree, 3.3x items, 2.3x distance numbers and the generalization-to-new-world result."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":478,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1556,"cache_read_input_tokens":21150,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1556,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqPKu1gjjz1acVPReq9","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"effa5b85-dc8e-4ef7-803e-cf4dec43f09a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:58.119Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"effa5b85-dc8e-4ef7-803e-cf4dec43f09a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Tob4Gsk5ZDJwqbYULwuZ93","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01FrcmC3enREsdskcwuZT8XP","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2409.07429v1","prompt":"Extract AWM's concrete mechanism: how does the workflow induction work (LLM extracts reusable sub-routines from past successful trajectories, given as natural-language workflow descriptions with steps)? In online mode, how does it induce workflows from its own solved test trajectories on the fly? How are workflows stored and injected into the agent's context/prompt for new tasks? How does it decide which trajectories are successful (verifier / reward)? Quote the 24.6% Mind2Web and 51.1% WebArena relative gains and the 8.9 to 14.0 absolute point generalization numbers."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":478,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1556,"cache_read_input_tokens":21150,"output_tokens":600,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1556},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":478,"output_tokens":600,"cache_read_input_tokens":21150,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1556,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1556,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqPKu1gjjz1acVPReq9","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"f2531a32-a90d-4d47-84c8-e558131d1c84","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:01.712Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"effa5b85-dc8e-4ef7-803e-cf4dec43f09a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01K9kH91j7K1j8aBdEnxrQjB","type":"tool_result","content":"# Voyager's Skill Library Mechanism\n\n## Skill Addition and Indexing\n\nSkills are added to the library only after successful task completion. According to the paper, \"Each time GPT-4 generates and verifies a new skill, we add it to the skill library, represented by a vector database.\" The indexing mechanism uses \"the embedding of the program description (generated by GPT-3.5)\" as the key, with the executable code itself as the value.\n\n## Skill Retrieval Process\n\nFor retrieval, the system queries the skill library with \"the embedding of self-generated task plans and environment feedback,\" returning the top-5 most relevant skills based on embedding similarity.\n\n## Self-Verification Gating Mechanism\n\nThe self-verification module acts as a critical gate for skill creation. Rather than manually coding success checkers, the system \"instantiate[s] another GPT-4 agent for self-verification. By providing Voyager's current state and the task to GPT-4, we ask it to act as a critic and inform us whether the program achieves the task.\"\n\nThis verification is \"more comprehensive than self-reflection by both checking success and reflecting on mistakes.\" Only upon successful verification does the system \"add this new skill to the skill library and ask the automatic curriculum for a new objective.\"\n\n## Skill Injection for New Tasks\n\nRetrieved skills are injected directly into prompts as \"Control primitive APIs, and relevant skills retrieved from the skill library, which are crucial for in-context learning.\"\n\n## Empirical Performance Metrics\n\n- **Tech tree mastery**: Voyager unlocks wooden tools \"15.3× faster,\" stone tools \"8.5× faster,\" and iron tools \"6.4× faster\"\n- **Item discovery**: \"3.3× more unique items\" than baselines\n- **Map traversal**: \"2.3× longer distances\"\n- **Generalization**: Voyager \"consistently solve[s] all the tasks\" in new worlds where baselines \"cannot solve any task\""}]},"uuid":"890b7091-f612-4a00-a45d-c90e84379c1f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:06.948Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":1461450,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Voyager's Skill Library Mechanism\n\n## Skill Addition and Indexing\n\nSkills are added to the library only after successful task completion. According to the paper, \"Each time GPT-4 generates and verifies a new skill, we add it to the skill library, represented by a vector database.\" The indexing mechanism uses \"the embedding of the program description (generated by GPT-3.5)\" as the key, with the executable code itself as the value.\n\n## Skill Retrieval Process\n\nFor retrieval, the system queries the skill library with \"the embedding of self-generated task plans and environment feedback,\" returning the top-5 most relevant skills based on embedding similarity.\n\n## Self-Verification Gating Mechanism\n\nThe self-verification module acts as a critical gate for skill creation. Rather than manually coding success checkers, the system \"instantiate[s] another GPT-4 agent for self-verification. By providing Voyager's current state and the task to GPT-4, we ask it to act as a critic and inform us whether the program achieves the task.\"\n\nThis verification is \"more comprehensive than self-reflection by both checking success and reflecting on mistakes.\" Only upon successful verification does the system \"add this new skill to the skill library and ask the automatic curriculum for a new objective.\"\n\n## Skill Injection for New Tasks\n\nRetrieved skills are injected directly into prompts as \"Control primitive APIs, and relevant skills retrieved from the skill library, which are crucial for in-context learning.\"\n\n## Empirical Performance Metrics\n\n- **Tech tree mastery**: Voyager unlocks wooden tools \"15.3× faster,\" stone tools \"8.5× faster,\" and iron tools \"6.4× faster\"\n- **Item discovery**: \"3.3× more unique items\" than baselines\n- **Map traversal**: \"2.3× longer distances\"\n- **Generalization**: Voyager \"consistently solve[s] all the tasks\" in new worlds where baselines \"cannot solve any task\"","durationMs":8608,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2305.16291"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"effa5b85-dc8e-4ef7-803e-cf4dec43f09a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"f2531a32-a90d-4d47-84c8-e558131d1c84","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FrcmC3enREsdskcwuZT8XP","type":"tool_result","content":"# Agent Workflow Memory: Concrete Mechanisms\n\n## Workflow Induction Process\n\n**LM-based extraction:** The system prompts language models to \"extract common sub-routines from one or more input experiences,\" identifying repetitive action patterns across successful trajectories. Rather than preserving example-specific details like \"dry cat food,\" the LM abstracts these into variables like \"{product-name}\" to enhance generalizability across similar tasks.\n\nEach induced workflow comprises two components:\n- A natural language description of the sub-task goal\n- A sequence of steps, where each step includes: environment state description, reasoning, and executable action\n\n## Online Mode Operation\n\nIn the online scenario, the agent follows this iterative loop for each test query:\n\n1. **Execution:** Agent attempts to solve the task, generating an action trajectory\n2. **Verification:** An LM-based evaluator judges success, outputting a binary label\n3. **Conditional induction:** If successful, workflows are extracted via: \"I⁢(eᵗ)→{wᵗ}\" (induction module processes the experience)\n4. **Memory update:** Successful workflows are added to agent memory for subsequent tasks: \"Mᵗ+{wᵗ}→Mᵗ⁺¹\"\n\n## Storage and Integration\n\nWorkflows are \"incorporated into the agent as auxiliary memory, M+𝒲→Mw,\" integrated into prompts/system instructions. When solving new tasks, the agent operates via: \"L(q,Mw,o)=L(q,M+W,o)→a,\" where the augmented memory guides action generation.\n\n## Success Detection\n\nThe system \"adopts the LM-based evaluation model\" that outputs binary success/failure judgments for trajectory evaluation.\n\n## Performance Gains\n\n- **Mind2Web:** 24.6% relative improvement in step-wise success rate\n- **WebArena:** 51.1% relative success rate increase over prior autonomous methods\n- **Generalization:** 8.9–14.0 absolute point improvements across cross-task, cross-website, and cross-domain scenarios, with margins widening as distribution gaps increase"}]},"uuid":"544773c1-09a1-4a85-ac1b-0d85c7f593d1","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:10.162Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":367917,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Agent Workflow Memory: Concrete Mechanisms\n\n## Workflow Induction Process\n\n**LM-based extraction:** The system prompts language models to \"extract common sub-routines from one or more input experiences,\" identifying repetitive action patterns across successful trajectories. Rather than preserving example-specific details like \"dry cat food,\" the LM abstracts these into variables like \"{product-name}\" to enhance generalizability across similar tasks.\n\nEach induced workflow comprises two components:\n- A natural language description of the sub-task goal\n- A sequence of steps, where each step includes: environment state description, reasoning, and executable action\n\n## Online Mode Operation\n\nIn the online scenario, the agent follows this iterative loop for each test query:\n\n1. **Execution:** Agent attempts to solve the task, generating an action trajectory\n2. **Verification:** An LM-based evaluator judges success, outputting a binary label\n3. **Conditional induction:** If successful, workflows are extracted via: \"I⁢(eᵗ)→{wᵗ}\" (induction module processes the experience)\n4. **Memory update:** Successful workflows are added to agent memory for subsequent tasks: \"Mᵗ+{wᵗ}→Mᵗ⁺¹\"\n\n## Storage and Integration\n\nWorkflows are \"incorporated into the agent as auxiliary memory, M+𝒲→Mw,\" integrated into prompts/system instructions. When solving new tasks, the agent operates via: \"L(q,Mw,o)=L(q,M+W,o)→a,\" where the augmented memory guides action generation.\n\n## Success Detection\n\nThe system \"adopts the LM-based evaluation model\" that outputs binary success/failure judgments for trajectory evaluation.\n\n## Performance Gains\n\n- **Mind2Web:** 24.6% relative improvement in step-wise success rate\n- **WebArena:** 51.1% relative success rate increase over prior autonomous methods\n- **Generalization:** 8.9–14.0 absolute point improvements across cross-task, cross-website, and cross-domain scenarios, with margins widening as distribution gaps increase","durationMs":8029,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2409.07429v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f2531a32-a90d-4d47-84c8-e558131d1c84","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"544773c1-09a1-4a85-ac1b-0d85c7f593d1","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_018zxGXfRAnZmzk5djyZXYht","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive mechanism details and exact numbers across all five systems. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Verifier-Fed Skill Learning: The Trajectory→Skill→Future-Task Loop\n\nThe five systems converge on the same loop shape: **(1) run a task and get a verdict → (2) abstract the trajectory into a generalized, reusable note/skill → (3) store it keyed by similarity → (4) retrieve top-k and inject into context for a *new* related task.** The verifier (pass/fail or test-log feedback) gates *what gets written* and, in some systems, prunes what survives. Below, each system's concrete mechanism plus the headline numbers.\n\n## 1. Letta — \"Skill Learning\" (the source of the +9% → +15.7% figures)\n\n**Source:** https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning (vendor blog; primary source for these specific numbers, but self-reported, not peer-reviewed).\n\n**The loop (two stages):**\n- **Reflection stage:** given a finished trajectory, an LLM produces an assessment of task success, reasoning soundness, edge-case handling, and explicitly looks for \"repetitive patterns or actions that could be abstracted.\" This stage can be *enriched with textual feedback from task verifiers* (e.g., test logs identifying failure modes).\n- **Creation stage:** a learning agent (Letta Code) invokes Anthropic's **skill-creator** to write a skill containing \"potential approaches, common pitfalls, and verification strategies.\"\n\n**Storage/retrieval/injection:** skills are stored as **modular markdown `.md` files**, git-manageable and shareable across an org. They live in the Letta filesystem and are accessed by the agent during execution (the blog does not spell out an embedding-similarity retrieval step the way Voyager/ExpeL do — it leans on the filesystem/skills harness).\n\n**The exact numbers (on Terminal-Bench 2.0, 89 tasks):**\n- **Trajectory-only skills:** +21.1% relative / **+9% absolute** success, plus **15.7% lower cost** and **10.4% fewer tool calls**.\n- **Trajectory + verifier feedback skills:** an *additional* +6.7%, for **+36.8% relative / +15.7% absolute** over baseline.\n\n**What drove the jump from +9% to +15.7%:** adding **verifier/test-log textual feedback** into the reflection stage. Feedback-informed skills encode \"common failure modes and unsuccessful approaches,\" which trajectory-only skills miss (a successful trajectory shows what worked but not what to avoid). *Reliability note: this is the cleanest direct answer to the question, but it is a single vendor benchmark run on one suite.*\n\n**Related Letta framing:** https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning argues learning should happen in *token/context space* not weights (interpretable, portable across model generations, checkpointable), and proposes \"sleep-time compute\" to consolidate/de-duplicate/abstract memory between sessions. No benchmark numbers in that post — it's the conceptual backdrop for skill learning.\n\n## 2. Voyager — skill library gated by self-verification\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16291 / https://arxiv.org/html/2305.16291 (peer-reviewed-adjacent, NVIDIA/Caltech, widely cited — high reliability).\n\n- **Extraction:** skills are **executable code** (JS Mineflayer programs). A skill is written only after the task is solved.\n- **Verifier gates writing:** a *separate GPT-4 instance acts as a critic* — given the agent's state + task, it judges whether the program achieved the goal. Only on a pass is the skill committed. This is \"more comprehensive than self-reflection\" because it both checks success and reflects on mistakes for the retry loop.\n- **Storage/retrieval:** vector DB keyed by the **embedding of a GPT-3.5-generated natural-language description** of the program; value is the code. For a new task, retrieve **top-5** by embedding similarity of the self-generated plan + environment feedback.\n- **Injection:** retrieved skills + control-primitive APIs go into the prompt as in-context examples; complex skills are *composed* from simpler stored ones (compounding, anti-catastrophic-forgetting).\n- **Numbers:** **3.3× more unique items, 2.3× longer distance, tech-tree milestones up to 15.3× faster** (wood 15.3×, stone 8.5×, iron 6.4×). Key generalization result: in a *fresh* Minecraft world the learned library lets Voyager solve novel tasks that baselines \"cannot solve any\" of.\n\n## 3. ExpeL — insight pool with vote-based pruning\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144 / https://arxiv.org/html/2308.10144v3 (AAAI 2024 — high reliability).\n\n- **Extraction (two channels):** (a) **compare success/fail trajectory pairs of the same task** to surface what distinguished the win; (b) extract common \"good practices\" from groups of L successes across different tasks.\n- **Verifier-driven refinement = the most explicit pruning mechanism here.** Insights live in a pool maintained by four LLM operations: **ADD** (new insight, importance count starts at 2), **EDIT** and **UPVOTE** (increment count), **DOWNVOTE** (decrement). **An insight is deleted when its importance hits zero.** This is the concrete \"prune skills\" answer.\n- **Retrieval/injection:** at inference, retrieve **top-k successful trajectories** by max inner-product task similarity (all-mpnet-base-v2 embeddings, Faiss), and inject **the full insight list + those top-k trajectories** as in-context guidance.\n- **Numbers (vs ReAct):** HotpotQA 39% vs 28%; ALFWorld 59% vs 40%; WebShop 49% vs 11%; **transfer** to FEVER 70% vs 63% (demonstrates source-task knowledge helping a *different* target task).\n\n## 4. Agent Workflow Memory (AWM) — induced reusable routines\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.07429 / https://arxiv.org/html/2409.07429v1 (CMU; Wang/Mao/Fried/Neubig — high reliability).\n\n- **Extraction by induction:** an LM extracts common **sub-routines (workflows)** from past successful trajectories, *abstracting* concrete details into variables (e.g., \"dry cat food\" → \"{product-name}\") for generalization. Each workflow = NL goal description + step sequence (state → reasoning → action).\n- **Verifier:** in **online** mode, after each test query the agent solves it, an **LM-based evaluator emits a binary success label**, and *only successful* trajectories are induced into workflows and added to memory (M + {w} → M'). This is the on-the-fly, no-training-set variant.\n- **Injection:** workflows become auxiliary memory folded into the system prompt for subsequent tasks.\n- **Numbers:** **+24.6% relative** success on Mind2Web, **+51.1% relative** on WebArena (plus fewer steps). Online AWM generalizes cross-task/site/domain by **+8.9 to +14.0 absolute points**, with the margin *widening* as the train/test gap grows — strong evidence the skills help on genuinely new tasks, not the same ones.\n\n## 5. Reflexion — verbal RL (the precursor; mostly same-task but the mechanism root)\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366 (NeurIPS 2023 — high reliability).\n\n- **Loop:** convert binary/scalar environment feedback into a **verbal self-reflection**, store it in an **episodic memory buffer**, and prepend it as context on the **next trial** of the task. The reflection acts as a \"semantic gradient.\"\n- **Verifier role:** the pass/fail signal is what's turned into the reflection — refinement *guided by* the verdict beats refinement alone by an **+8% absolute** boost over plain episodic memory.\n- *Caveat for this angle:* Reflexion primarily improves *retries of the same task* across trials, not transfer to new tasks. It's the conceptual root that ExpeL/AWM/Letta extend toward cross-task reuse.\n\n---\n\n## Synthesis — the common verifier-fed loop\n1. **Solve + judge:** run the trajectory; a verifier (env reward, separate-LLM critic, or test logs) yields pass/fail + optional textual diagnosis.\n2. **Abstract, don't memorize:** an LLM induces a *generalized* artifact — code skill (Voyager), NL insight (ExpeL), workflow with variables (AWM), markdown skill with pitfalls + verification strategy (Letta). Variabilizing/abstracting is what makes it help *future* tasks.\n3. **Gate on the verdict:** only verified-good experiences are written (Voyager, AWM); failures feed the *content* of the note (\"what to avoid\") rather than being discarded — this is exactly Letta's +9%→+15.7% lever.\n4. **Store by similarity, retrieve top-k, inject:** embedding-keyed vector store with top-5/top-k retrieval (Voyager, ExpeL) or filesystem/memory blocks (Letta, AWM); inject as in-context examples/auxiliary memory.\n5. **Prune:** ExpeL's UPVOTE/DOWNVOTE-to-zero is the most concrete pruning; Letta proposes sleep-time consolidation; others mainly accrete.\n\n**Most relevant for the Yogi build:** ExpeL's vote-based insight pruning and AWM's verifier-gated online induction are the most directly implementable \"verifier refines/prunes skills\" mechanisms; Letta's blog is the source of the specific +9%/+15.7% Terminal-Bench-2.0 numbers and confirms that **verifier feedback in the reflection step is the differentiating ingredient.**\n\n**Reliability summary:** Voyager, ExpeL, AWM, Reflexion are peer-reviewed/established papers (high confidence). The Letta +9%/+15.7% figures are vendor-self-reported on a single benchmark run (directionally credible, treat the exact magnitudes with appropriate caution)."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2461,"cache_read_input_tokens":22706,"output_tokens":3505,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2461},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":3505,"cache_read_input_tokens":22706,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2461,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2461,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqQgxa5JYdT15Ee2u2d","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"c960d397-32c1-4b20-bd6b-8c329220cda3","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:57.263Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
